05076nam a22006015i 9780226822457DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226822457  a(DE-B1597)633881  a(OCoLC)1348488560  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aP119.32.U6bK83 2022 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a306.44223/eng/202203161 aKuklick, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFascism Comes to America :bA Century of Obsession in Politics and Culture /cBruce Kuklick. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b22 halftones, 1 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Expressing Fascism -- tPart I 1909–49 -- tWhy Fascism? -- t1 Fascism before Fascism, 1909–35 -- t2 Franklin Roosevelt and Political Culture, 1932–36 -- t3 Perplexity at Home and Abroad, 1934–38 -- t4 Foreign and Domestic Contradictions, 1938–40 -- t5 The Coming of the War, 1939–42 -- t6 Fascism Penetrates Popular Life, 1936–49 -- tPart II 1942–2020 -- tPerforming Words -- t7 Fascism on the Right, 1942–70 -- t8 Europeans Bring Fascism to the States -- t9 Fascism Triumphs over Communism -- t10 Scholars Approach Fascism -- t11 Fascism Everywhere, 1970–2020 -- t12 Democracy and Fascism -- tConclusion: Fascism without Fascism -- tNotes, Sources, and Methods -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA deeply relevant look at what fascism means to Americans. From the time Mussolini took power in Italy in 1922, Americans have been obsessed with and brooded over the meaning of fascism and how it might migrate to the United States. Fascism Comes to America examines how we have viewed fascism overseas and its implications for our own country. Bruce Kuklick explores the rhetoric of politicians, who have used the language of fascism to smear opponents, and he looks at the discussions of pundits, the analyses of academics, and the displays of fascism in popular culture, including fiction, radio, TV, theater, and film. Kuklick argues that fascism has little informational meaning in the United States, but instead, it is used to denigrate or insult. For example, every political position has been besmirched as fascist. As a result, the term does not describe a phenomenon so much as it denounces what one does not like. Finally, in displaying fascism for most Americans, entertainment—and most importantly film—has been crucial in conveying to citizens what fascism is about. Fascism Comes to America has been enhanced by many illustrations that exhibit how fascism was absorbed into the US public consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFascismzUnited States. 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apopular culture, rhetoric, politics, government, politicians, denigration, nonfiction, mussolini, italy, hitler, germany, mudslinging, political opponents, pundits, entertainment, film, television, radio, theater, insult, denounce, ideology, public opinion, repression, oppression, resistance, dictator, control, fear, paranoia, free speech, injustice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eB